ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[HFMD is predominantly a disease of childhood, usually associated with
coxsackievirus A16 or enterovirus 71 infection, and less frequently with
various other A and B coxsackieviruses. More severe disease in a minority
of patients has been associated with enterovirus 71 infection in some Asian
countries. Typical cases of HFMD have vesicles and ulcers in the mouth and
on the tongue, and a vesicular exanthem usually located on the palms and
soles. Recovery from HFMD is usually complete within 1 or 2 weeks. - Mod.CP]
